\c 22
\s Rules about stealing
\p
\v 1 “If someone steals a ox or sheep, and then kills and sells it, then he must replace a bull with five boxes, and a sheep with four sheep.
\p
\v 2 “If a theft is caught when entering someone’s house and the theft is killed, then the person who killed him is not guilty.
\v 3 But if that incident happens during day time, then the murderer is guilty for that murder.
\p “A theft must repay the loss over all that he stole. If he is usable to pay for the loss, then he will be sold as a slave to pay off all that he already stole.
\v 4 If a ox, donkey, or sheep that he stole is found with him in an alive condition, then he has to compensate the loss twice (the value).
\s Rule about guarding plants ina field
\p
\v 5 “If someone lets his livestock eat grass in the field or vineyard he owns, then the livestock come loose and and roam (and) ate other people’s animals, then the owner of that animal must compensate for the loss to the owner of that animal by giving the best harvest from his field or vineyard.
\p
\v 6 “When someone turns on fire and that fire devours thorn bushes and spreads to other people’s field, so that it burns piles of wheat harves or wheat plants on the field, or burns the whole of that field, then he must pay full compensation.”
\s Rules about protecting personal property
\p
\v 7 If a person entrusts money or goods to his friend, and the entrusted (money) is stolen from his friend’s house, then if the theft is caught, he must pay double compensation.
\v 8 But if the theft is not caught, the nthe owner of that house must appear before the judges,\f + \fr 22:8 \fk the judges \ft The word ‘ha-elohim’ (plural) that is translated ‘the judges’ in this verse and verse 9 may also be translated as ‘before God’. Case courts like this is often executed by judges from the Tribe of Levi in the Holy Tent location.\f*so that they determine whether he stole his friend’s (goods) or not.
\p
\v 9 “If two people have a dispute, each of them claim to be the owner of anything that is lost— including ox, donkey, sheep, clothing, or other goods, then both parties must appear before the judges and the judges will decide which party is guilty. The guilty person must pay double to the real owner.
\p
\v 10 “If a person entrusts a donkey, ox, sheep, or other animals to his friend, and then the animal dies or is injured or robbed by enemies and not even a person sees the incident,
\v 11 then the friend must vow before the LORD that he did not take that animal. The owner of that animal must accept the vow of the friend and the friend does not need to compensate for the loss.
\v 12 But if in fact the animal was stolen from his friend, then his friend must pay compensation for the loss to the owner.
\v 13 If in fact the animal is attacked by a wild animal and he can show the carcass as an evidence, then he does not need to pay compensation for the loss over that animal.
\p
\v 14 “If someone borrows an animal from his friend, and then the animal is injured or dies when the owner is not there, then he must pay compensation for the loss completely.
\v 15 But if the owner is there when it happened, then the person who borrows it does not have to pay compensation. If that animal is a rented animal, then he does not need to compensate because the loss has already been taken into account for in the rent fee.”
\s Rules about social justice
\p
\v 16 “If a man seduces a virgin who is not yet engaged and has sexual relations with her, then he must pay the dowry for that woman and marry her.
\v 17 If the father of that woman refuses to marry his daughter, then he still must pay for the dowry for a virgin.”
\s Violations with a death sentence
\p
\v 18 “Don’t let a magician lady stay alive.
\p
\v 19 “Everyone who has sex with animals must be killed.
\p
\v 20 “Whoever offers animal sacrifice to other god aside from the LORD, must be destroyed(made vanish).”
\s Rules for those who do oppression
\p
\v 21 “Don’t oppress foreigners. Remember that before you are foreigners in Egypt.
\p
\v 22 “Don’t oppress widows and orphans.
\v 23 If you oppress them and they cry out to Me, then I will defend them.
\v 24 You will awaken My anger and I will kill you with sword. Your wives will become widows and your children will become orphans.
\p
\v 25 “If there are any among you who lends money to one of My people who are poor among you, don’t act like a debt collector by charging interest to him.
\v 26 If you take your friend’s coat as a debt guarantee, return the coat before the sun goes down,
\v 27 because maybe that coat is his only one and he needs it when he sleeps. If you don’t return it and he cries to Me for help, I will listen to him and I will consider youguilty, becuase I am merciful.”
\s Honoring God
\p
\v 28 “Don’t blaspheme God or curse the leaders of your nation.
\p
\v 29 “Don’t delay in offering your first harvests of the field and vineyard. Offer your firstborn sons to Me.
\p
\v 30 “LIkewise with your firstborn cows and sheep, let the offsprings live with their mother for seven days, and offer them to Me on the eighth day.
\p
\v 31 “You must become holy people for Me. Therefore, don’t eat the meat of animals that are killed by wild animal. Give the meat to the dogs.”